ABUJA â€“ Justice Inyang Ekwo of the Federal High Court sitting in Abuja has discharged and acquitted a former Minister of Special Duties and Inter-Governmental Affairs, Kabiru Turaki SAN. Turaki served as a Minister under the administration of former President Goodluck Jonathan between 2013 and 2015. He also served as supervising Minister for Federal Ministry of Labour between 2014 and 2015. He was prosecuted by the Federal Government on a 16-count charge, bordering on allegation of unlawful and criminal misappropriation of N715 million. The charge was filed by the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission. The EFCC had arraigned the former Minister (1st defendant) alongside his former Special Assistant, Sampson Okpetu (2nd defendant), and two firms; Samtee Essentials Ltd and Pasco Investment Ltd, on money laundering allegations. Although the duo pleaded not guilty to the charges, the anti-graft agency alleged that the defendants used the companies to launder funds. totally about N845 million stolen from the two ministries where the minister held sway under the then administration. Delivering judgement on Monday, the trial Judge, Justice Inyang Ekwo, said the prosecution have not been able to link the former minister and his codefendants with the offences contained in the 16-count charge. POLL According to the Judge, the defendants dislodged the evidences of the prosecution witnesses called in the matter during cross examination. He said, it was established during cross examination that Turaki was not a signatory to the account of the ministry and did not authorize any payment or make any transfer of funds. The court held that the former minister was not a member of the ministerial tenders board and that there was no inflow of funds from the account of the ministry to the company of the former minister